<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Urge Review of Military Treaty With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials Urge Review of Military Treaty With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    President Urges Study of Issues </H4>

<F P=102> PA1904195794 Tegucigalpa LA TRIBUNA in Spanish 19 Apr 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> PA1904195794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tegucigalpa LA TRIBUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The Honduran Armed Forces want to break the 
Military Assistance Treaty signed in 1954 with the U.S. 
Government because they believe the treaty is obsolete and is no 
longer of any benefit to the nation. 
  The above was reported by CNN international, which also said 
that the presence of U.S. troops in Latin America continues to 
cause problems for some nations of the region. [passage omitted] 
  When questioned about the issue, President Carlos Roberto 
Reina commented: "We should study the issue and see if this 
installation can benefit Honduras and our new agenda." 
  To end the treaty, the CNN report concluded, is the 
prerogative of the president. Meanwhile, the Armed Forces are 
trying to obtain the support of civilians to achieve their goal. 

</TEXT>

