<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rumor of Attack on Castro Linked to U.S. Radio Station </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rumor of Attack on Castro Linked to U.S. Radio Station </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2004215894 Paris AFP in Spanish 2120 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2004215894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 20 Apr (AFP) -- President Fidel Castro Ruz 
is "in perfect health," a Cuban Foreign Ministry representative 
stated Wednesday, denying rumors spread abroad of an attack on 
the Cuban leader or his hospitalization. 
  According to the source questioned by AFP, the head of state 
participated as scheduled in an "official function" on Tuesday 
[19 April] night. Nevertheless, rumors apparently started by a 
Florida radio station spread in several Latin American 
countries, claiming Fidel Castro had been the victim of an 
attack or had been hospitalized in the CIMEQ [expansion unknown] 
-- one of the best hospitals in Havana. 
  In Washington, a U.S. State Department spokesman announced 
the United States had no information that enabled it to confirm 
or deny any version of the story, and he noted there was no 
"indication" of a change in the situation in Cuba. 
  In fact, the situation was completely normal on Wednesday in 
Havana, where most Foreign Ministry officials were preparing for 
a conference which, from Friday to Sunday, will bring together 
representatives of the Cuban Government and some 200 members of 
the Cuban community living abroad. 

</TEXT>

