<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Chief on Rising U.S. Interest Rate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Central Bank Chief on Rising U.S. Interest Rate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1904214394 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1924 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1904214394 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Buenos Aires, 19 Apr (NA) -- Central Bank 
President Roque Fernandez today said the interest rate increase 
in the United States is going to cause an increase in the local 
interest rates on deposits, and he believes that during the rest 
of the year there will be "ups and downs in the markets as a 
result of the U.S. Federal Reserve's policy." 
  The banker indicated that the increase in the U.S. interest 
rate is going to cause an increase in the interest rates on 
deposits, and "this is an incentive to save, something that is 
not bad." 
  "It is bad when the active rates on loans increase," he 
said, 
and explained that monetary authorities are studying "how this 
incentive on the passive rate will favor savings." 
  The measure the Central Bank has under study is a decrease 
in 
the spread [preceding word in English], in other words, banking 
costs, "so the active interest rate will remain where it is." 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

