<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chile To Keep Pace in Weapons Purchasing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chile To Keep Pace in Weapons Purchasing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1904221594 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1941 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1904221594 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 19 Apr (NA) -- The Chilean national 
defense chief of staff, Vice Admiral Jorge Patricio Arancibia 
Reyes, stated today in this capital that Chile will continue to 
purchase armaments because "the technological level that has 
been acquired, which is related to the level of a country's 
development, cannot be neglected." 
  "A country must have the armed forces it is capable of 
maintaining, both technologically and financially, in a close 
relationship between security and development," Arancibia Reyes 
said. 
  Notwithstanding, the admiral denied that Chile is embarked 
on 
an arms race, and said "materiel only has been renewed" in 
recent times. 
  Asked about the appearance of insurgent groups in several 
parts of the continent, such as the group that revolted in 
Chiapas, Mexico, he maintained that today "they have an 
international structure behind them that keeps their concern 
about these movements on the alert." [quote as received] 
  The Chilean Army chief [title as received], who is visiting 
the country on an official visit, today met Argentine Defense 
Minister Oscar Camilion. 
  During the meeting, in which the Argentine joint chief of 
staff, Lieutenant General Mario Candido Diaz, participated, the 
Chilean officer handed a letter to Camilion from Chilean Defense 
Minister Edmundo Perez Yoma, who proposed a meeting between the 
two ministers some time this year. 
  Regarding the Mapuche conflict that has emerged in his 
country, Arancibia Reyes stressed that "a solution is in the 
works," and that "the concerns expressed by the Mapuches are 
being well channeled." 
  Finally, Arancibia Reyes highlighted "the greatness of the 
Argentine Armed Forces" within the Latin American context. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

