<H3> <TI>   Justice Minister: Traffickers' Sentences Lax </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Justice Minister: Traffickers' Sentences Lax </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2004185194 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2004185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] The Colombian Government today admitted punishment 
for drug traffickers is very lax and suggested that sentences be 
doubled through changes in the law. The recommendation is not 
designed to make changes to the frequently discussed Procedural 
Code but to the Penal Code. 
  [Begin Justice Minister Andres Gonzalez recording] What is 
obvious is that the sentences need to be significantly harsher, 
and there are several reasons for this. I believe that current 
sentences should be at least doubled. [end recording] 
  Justice Minister Gonzalez said that for the government's 
policy to be successful, stronger sentences for drug traffickers 
must be accompanied by appropriate interpretations of the system 
used to reduce sentences. 
  [Begin Gonzalez recording] I believe there are many 
loopholes 
certain lawyers use to get sentences reduced. These loopholes 
are not included in the law. [end recording] 
  It is very clear to the government that some of the 
guidelines established in light of the internal unrest and 
former state of siege gave the drug traffickers too many 
advantages, and, in turn, these advantages resulted in absurd 
sentences. 

</TEXT>

