<DATE1>  19 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaviria: Human Rights Report Lacks Objectivity </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gaviria: Human Rights Report Lacks Objectivity </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2004162994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0028 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2004162994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cartagena de Indias (Colombia), 18 Apr (EFE) -- 
Colombian President Cesar Gaviria described today as "lacking in 
objectivity" a report issued by Amnesty International (AI) 
requesting the United States suspension of military aid to the 
Colombian Armed Forces, which AI accused of violating human 
rights. 
  "I have never denied there are human rights problems, but 
international organizations are not properly assessing things 
taking place in Colombia to protect fundamental principles," 
Gaviria stated to reporters in the Caribbean city of Cartagena 
de Indias. 
  AI, a human rights organization headquartered in London, 
asked the United States to suspend economic aid to the Colombian 
military because "the Colombian Armed Forces are a bridge for 
the violation of the rights of individuals." 
  According to the Colombian president, AI "lacks objectivity" 
in reporting how Colombia has managed the situation and how 
Colombia has protected human rights in past years, especially 
after the new National Constitution was promulgated in 1991. 
  The Colombian president underscored that the Armed Forces, 
when they combat insurgents, "cannot ever fall into the trap of 
imitating the guerrillas' behavior of intimidation, extortion, 
torture, kidnapping, and slaying and injuring soldiers and 
policemen, or putting them out of action." 
  Gaviria added: "Colombia has confronted persistent attacks 
against its democratic institutions for many years. The attacks 
come from organizations that receive economic resources from 
kidnapping and extortion activities." 
  He added, "To confront these groups, there is an 
overwhelming 
majority of members of the military and police forces who 
respect the law." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11083 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat077_t_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-077 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Caldera Says Constituent Assembly Will Not Solve Problems </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Caldera Says Constituent Assembly Will Not Solve Problems </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2004163094 Caracas EL DIARIO DE CARACAS in Spanish 15 Apr 
94 p 27 </F>

<F P=103> PA2004163094 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas EL DIARIO DE CARACAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Rafael Caldera said yesterday that 
summoning a constituent assembly is not the solution to the 
country's problems. He also urged the Congress to include the 
impeachment referendum in the constitutional amendments to 
create a "truly participative" democracy. 
  The president noted Colombia's positive experience in this 
area, adding that it is possible to reform the system "without 
breaking the constitutional thread." 
  Speaking during the presentation of the book Venezuela, 
Crisis and Constitutional Reform at the Avila Hotel, he 
said he was among those who think the congressional debate on 
the reform should begin where the past legislature left off. In 
any case, a bicameral commission should be named to promptly 
update the study and to include new proposals. Caldera indicated 
four kinds of referenda must be included in the reforms: a 
referendum to impeach, a referendum to consult, a referendum to 
approve, and a referendum to confirm. As an example, he said a 
matter as important as the delimitation of marine and underwater 
areas with Colombia must be submitted to a popular consultation, 
"because a mere ratification by Congress would not be 
sufficient." 
  Regarding federalism, Caldera explained he views it as the 
adequate strengthening of administrative decentralization that 
avoids "the destructive abuses" of centralism but does not 
restore the vices of the old system of cronyism. 
  "I have been asked, not without malice, if now as president 
I 
continue supporting the possibility of revoking the mandate of 
the head of state and any top official, and I have said I would 
feel bad if it were not approved," he warned. The president said 
he is confident that the congressional debates will have a 
favorable outcome and that the stumbling blocks to a favorable 
outcome will be removed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

