<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lage Comments on Emigre Conference, Dialogue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lage Comments on Emigre Conference, Dialogue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2104193494 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2104193494 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] During a recent visit to Granma Province, Carlos 
Lage Davila, member of the Politburo and secretary of the 
Council of Ministers, made important statements regarding the 
Nation and the Emigre Community conference, which begins on 22 
April in Havana. 
  [Begin Lage recording] It is important. We have always 
maintained a dialogue with sectors of the Cuban community abroad 
that maintain a position of respect toward the Revolution, 
acknowledge the Revolution, and condemn the blockade policy. I 
would say that this is what shapes our relations with certain 
sectors of the emigre community. 
  With those sectors of that community who support the goals 
of 
U.S. policy -- blockade and hostility toward the Revolution, 
there is not, nor can there be any type of ties. 
  In this context, this conference is important. There is the 
precedent of the previous meeting in 1978, if I remember well. 
That conference did not have a proper follow-up because the U.S. 
policy was progressively hardened and affected, and is still 
affecting normal ties between Cuba and the emigre community. 
Those ties are damaged because they are hampered by U.S. policy. 
We believe that this meeting will make progress in this regard 
and could represent an important step to strengthen 
communication and ties, and above all, policies and the struggle 
against the blockade. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

