<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-078 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Warns To Expect `Flood' of Refugees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Warns To Expect `Flood' of Refugees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2104220494 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2104220494 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Haitian President-in-exile Jean-Bertrand Aristide 
has warned the United States that he cannot prevent a flood of 
Haitian refugees from landing on U.S. coasts if democracy is not 
restored in his country. Furthermore, Father Aristide, who was 
speaking in front of the World Affairs Council [previous three 
words in English] in San Francisco on 18 April, reproached the 
Clinton government for giving the impression of withdrawing in 
the face of armed bands supported by the Haitian military. In 
the face of some hooligans, the most powerful country in the 
world cannot pretend that they are stronger than they, he 
asserted, pointing up until now he had urged his partisans to 
remain in Haiti to work for democracy instead of trying to reach 
the coasts of Florida. 
  Aristide pointed out that henceforth it would be cynical to 
maintain this recommendation in light of U.S. inaction. The 
Clinton administration said last week that it would continue to 
follow the democratic path while seeking a solution, but that it 
did not exclude other options. The day before, the president of 
the Appropriations Committee of the House of Representatives 
requested U.S. military intervention to put an end to the 
military regime in Haiti. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

