<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The former president of the lower chamber, 
Deputy Antoine Joseph, called on the Army and the private sector 
on 20 April to take a stand against the clean sweep policy and 
the implementation of Article 149. Deputy Joseph deems the 
demands of some political sectors that demand the return of 
President Aristide 10 days after the appointment of a new prime 
minister unrealistic. 
  [Begin Joseph recording, in Creole] Certain solutions that 
have been proposed are supported by some sectors. I can put 
myself in the shoes of the private sector. I very much doubt 
that the private sector would have an interest in supporting the 
implementation of Art. 149. This is also my private position. 
Personally, I think the country is not ready to face the 
political and financial consequences of the implementation of 
Art. 149. [passage omitted] [end recording] 
  Furthermore, Deputy Joseph reaffirmed his support for the 
initiative of the president of the Chamber of Deputies to begin 
consultations with the various sectors involved in the crisis. 
