<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2104222494 </F>
<F P=103> PY2104222494 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 21 April. 
  The National Statistics Institute reported that the Bolivian 
trade balance registered a $445.2 million deficit in 1993 with 
exports at $804.1 million and imports at $1.2493 billion, a 10.5 
percent increase compared with 1992. Exports of nontraditional 
products registered the highest increase with 27.6 percent. 
Hydrocarbon exports dropped 27 percent compared with 1992. (La 
Paz LA RAZON in Spanish 7 Apr 94 p B5) 
  The Superintendency of Banks reported that banks' deposits 
totalled $2.0761 billion through 31 March, of which $1.9387 
billion came from the private sector and $137.4 million from the 
public sector. (La Paz HOY in Spanish 7 Apr 94 Economic Section 
p 17) 
  The Bolivian Central Bank reported that the fiscal deficit 
was $150 million in the year's first three months, a drop of 50 
percent compared with the same period in 1992, when it was $305 
million. International reserves went from $223.7 million in the 
first three months of 1993 to $368.6 million in the same period 
this year, an increase of 64.8 percent in 12 months. (La Paz LA 
RAZON in Spanish 8 Apr 94 Economic Section p B5) 

</TEXT>

