<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Czech Prime Minister Arrives on Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Czech Prime Minister Arrives on Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2104203094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0146 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2104203094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santiago, 20 Apr (EFE) -- Chilean President Eduardo 
Frei today compared the return to democracy in Chile and the 
Czech Republic -- which took place simultaneously and in a 
civilized manner, free of any bloodshed. 
  Frei said this during a dinner party to fete Czech Prime 
Minister Vaclav Klaus who arrived from Buenos Aires today for a 
three-day official visit to Chile. 
  Frei said that the Chilean and Czech Governments "uphold 
broad respect for human rights and fully enforce the multiparty 
system." 
  The Chilean chief of state pointed out that "both countries 
enjoy a similar degree of development and uphold the 
effectiveness of an open international trade which is not 
discriminatory. They are against restrictions that prevent it 
from being clear." 
  Frei added: "In the four years since March 1990, Chile and 
the Czech Republic have come closer on several issues and have 
made efforts to build solid and fruitful relations." 
  Chile and the former Czechoslovakia resumed diplomatic 
relations at the ambassadorial level on 11 March 1990, when 
Patricio Aylwin's civilian administration assumed power, ending 
almost 17 years of General Augusto Pinochet's military regime. 
  Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus will meet with Chilean public 
and 
private sector officials and will end his visit to Santiago on 
22 April with the signing of a broad cooperation agreement in 
the areas of culture, education, and science. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11136 </DOCNO>
