<H3> <TI>   Bahia Governor To Run in General Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bahia Governor To Run in General Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2104033494 Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 
2200 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2104033494 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Salete Sodreira from Brasilia] </F>
  [Text] The Federal Supreme Court, STF, upheld the Bahia 
State law allowing the local legislative assembly to indirectly 
elect former Governor Antonio Carlos Magalhaes' successor. 
  The former governor resigned his position to run in the 3 
October general elections. The Bahia legislative assembly had 
approved a law allowing the election of a successor to finish 
the gubernatorial mandate. A group of parties resorted to the 
STF, stating that the law was unconstitutional because 
gubernatorial elections must be handled by Congress. They also 
alleged that voting for the successor could not be open as 
established in Bahia State law. By a seven-four vote, the STF 
justices ruled the state law was based on the Constitution and 
that Gov. Antonio Carlos Magalhaes' successor must be elected in 
30 days. Vice Governor Paulo Souto also resigned his position to 
run in the October elections. 

</TEXT>

