<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nation, Emigre Community Conference Begins </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nation, Emigre Community Conference Begins </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Lage Presents Economic Analysis </H4>

<F P=102> FL2504005694 Havana Radio Reloj Network in Spanish 2001 GMT 
24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2504005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Reloj Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Carlos Lage, secretary of the Executive Committee of 
the Council of Ministers, presented to participants of the 
Nation and the Emigre Community Conference an analysis on the 
current situation of the economy, and its prospects. Lage's 
presentation brought about an exchange of ideas by Cuban 
authorities and the more than 200 residents from abroad who are 
attending the forum. 
  The Nation and the Emigre Community Conference will conclude 
today at 2030 GMT and according to Miguel Alfonso, spokesman for 
the conference, the debate has retained an elevated tone of 
respect. Especially notable was the positive attitude toward the 
fatherland. 
  The meeting was inaugurated on Friday with speeches by 
Ricardo Alarcon and Abel Prieto, presidents of the National 
Assembly of the People's Government and the National Union of 
Cuban Writers and Artists, respectively, and by Cuban Foreign 
Minister Roberto Robaina. 
  Among the decisions adopted during the conference with the 
emigre community were: continuation of contacts and exchanges to 
promote the normalization of relations, creation of an office to 
take care of emigration issues, and creation of a specialized 
magazine for that sector. The elimination of the five-year 
waiting period for those who abandoned the country to legally 
return, and abolition of the requirement for them to obtain 
reservations in hotels, were other measures discussed. 
  Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina also informed 
participants at the conference of the government's willingness 
to facilitate cultural links reaffirming their Cuban nature. 
  The meeting was devised by our country in an attempt to 
identify common problems between the nation and the emigre 
community and to promote solutions to those problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

