<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zamora Concerned by Poor Voter Turnout </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zamora Concerned by Poor Voter Turnout </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2404201494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1908 GMT 24 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2404201494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] San Salvador, 24 Apr (NOTIMEX) -- Ruben Zamora, 
presidential candidate for the leftist coalition, here today 
said that he is worried by the poor turnout of voters this 
morning when the voting sites opened. 
  "Very early this morning I toured the city and saw that the 
turnout of voters was poor and this worries me," Zamora said. 
Zamora is the presidential candidate for the leftist coalition 
headed by the former rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation 
Front (FMLN). "I ask the Salvadorans to think of what is 
happening and to go and vote," Zamora said when calling on the 
2.7 million registered voters to consider the importance this 
election has on the future of the country and to go out and cast 
their vote. 
  The presidential candidate admitted that the electoral 
authorities corrected the mistakes reported during the first 
election held on 20 March. At that time, none of the parties 
that participated in the election attained the necessary 
majority -- half plus one of the votes cast -- to become 
president of the Republic. For this reason, the Supreme 
Electoral Tribunal [TSE] called for a run-off election between 
the two leading candidates. 
  Thus, Zamora and Nationalist Republican Alliance [ARENA] 
candidate Armando Calderon Sol confronted each other today to 
decide which of the two will be president for the 1994-1999 term. 
  Zamora has said that the experience gained in the first 
round 
made it possible for the coalition to be more alert at voting 
sites and prevent irregularities and fraud attempts. 
  The TSE called the 2.7 million citizens with voting rights 
to 
go to the 381 voting sites, spread throughout the country's 262 
municipalities. The election started at 0700 local (1300 GMT) 
and will close at 1700 (2300 GMT). The TSE expects to release 
the results of at least 30 percent of the vote four hours after 
closing time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
