<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Supreme Court Suspends Legislative Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Supreme Court Suspends Legislative Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2304155794 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1509 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2304155794 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["14 August Elections Temporarily Suspended" -- ACAN </F>
headline] 
  [Text] Guatemala City, 23 Apr (ACAN-EFE) -- The legislative 
elections scheduled for 4 August [date as received] in Guatemala 
were temporarily suspended after the Supreme Court of Justice 
(CSJ) approved an amparo filed by Deputy Carlos Humberto 
Arroyave. 
  The Solidarity Action Movement (MAS) legislator, who held a 
seat during deposed coupist President Jorge Serrano's 
(1991-1993) administration, claimed that the call for elections 
violated his political rights. 
  In confirming the temporary suspension of the electoral 
process, a Supreme Electoral Tribunal (TSE) magistrate said 
today that his organization accepts but does not share the CSJ 
ruling. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11201 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat079_g_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   President: Elections To Be Held 14 Aug </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President: Elections To Be Held 14 Aug </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2404153894 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1759 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2404153894 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 23 Apr (ACAN-EFE) -- Today 
Guatemalan President Ramiro De Leon Carpio reiterated his 
confidence that legislative elections scheduled for 14 August 
will be held accordingly. De Leon told the media that the 
temporary suspension of the elections by a Supreme Court of 
Justice resolution is "temporary," and that the Constitutional 
Court will be the one to resolve the case definitively once it 
is submitted. 
  De Leon did not make any comments on whether or not the 
Supreme Court of Justice decision to protect Solidarity Action 
Movement deputy Carlos Humberto Arroyave was a political one. "I 
respect the autonomy of government branches," De Leon replied. 
  De Leon added that from an electoral viewpoint, the amparo 
Arroyave filed charging that the Supreme Electoral Tribunal 
violated his rights by convening legislative elections on 14 
August has political overtones since he is a congressional 
deputy. De Leon indicated that those actions are allowed within 
a system of legality and a de jure regime and that the Court 
resolution shows that legal and democratic systems are at work 
in Guatemala. De Leon expressed his confidence in the integrity 
of Court magistrates, who convened elections based on legal 
considerations and in accordance with constitutional reforms. 
  Political leaders, including retired General Efrain Rios 
Montt, former head of the de facto government, and Francisco 
Reyes, both of whom are members of the Guatemalan Republican 
Front, maintain that the Court resolution was political because 
the magistrates do not want to leave their posts either. 
  Following the election of a new legislative assembly, new 
Court magistrates will be appointed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

