<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Czech Prime Minister Announces Visa Elimination Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Czech Prime Minister Announces Visa Elimination Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2204134194 Santiago Radio Cooperativa Network in Spanish 
1100 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2204134194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago Radio Cooperativa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus has promised to 
eliminate visas for Chileans who want to visit Czechoslovakia. 
The prime minister reported that Chile and the Czech Republic 
have completed an agreement to eliminate entrance visas. 
  The Czech prime minister made this comment at the end of a 
lecture he gave to international affairs experts at the Andres 
Bello Diplomatic Institute in the Foreign Ministry building. 
  In his lecture the Czech prime minister said he is in Chile 
because he believes that his nation must not restrict its ties 
to European countries only. 
  Klaus expressed skepticism about the idea of a great 
European 
union, but he said he favors an integration process that admits 
diversity. He also said that the Czech Government is interested 
in safeguarding its own identity without, he said, dissolving in 
coffee like a lump of sugar. In addition, he warned that the 
Czech Republic does not intend to become a bridge between 
eastern and western Europe. 

</TEXT>

