<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Criticizes Protectionism </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister Criticizes Protectionism </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2204143194 Santiago LA TERCERA DE LA HORA in Spanish 13 
Apr 94 Economic Section p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PY2204143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago LA TERCERA DE LA HORA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Finance Minister Eduardo Aninat said yesterday that 
"Chile is against protectionism and the formation of closed 
trade blocs, as we want to avoid having the world fall into 
trade wars that are harmful to trade and investment." Aninat 
made this comment in a speech before the Inter-American 
Development Bank (IDB) Assembly in Guadalajara, Mexico. 
  He added that Chile will use every international meeting to 
denounce this practice. He noted that "after long efforts to 
increase the quantity and variety of its goods and services, 
Chile is operating with an export capability of 33 percent to 
the Latin American countries, 31.8 percent to Europe, and 31 
percent to Asia. [no closing quotation marks as published] 
  Aninat also proposed the formation of open and sophisticated 
regional groups for investment and international trade. 
  He added that the Chilean Government was pleased to hear the 
reaffirmation made by U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor 
that Chile continues to be the primary candidate for joining 
NAFTA [North American Free Trade Agreement], made up of the 
United States, Mexico, and Canada, or for negotiating a 
bilateral agreement "because we are not against either of the 
two formulas," said Aninat. 
  Aninat also recognized the contribution made by the IDB for 
regional integration. He expressed optimism that this 
organization would support the hemispheric summit called by 
President Bill Clinton in Miami next December. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

