<H3> <TI>   Attorney General Warns on Mass Prisoner Release </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Attorney General Warns on Mass Prisoner Release </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2204205394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2204205394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] The government might again declare a state of 
internal disturbance before 2 May. Special measures would have 
to be taken to prevent -- for the third time -- the possible 
mass release of terrorists and drug traffickers from the 
country's prisons. 
  In a letter, the attorney general [Carlos Gustavo Arrieta] 
warned the prosecutor general [Gustavo de Greiff] that if the 
legal situation is not defined for narcoterrorists and 
guerrillas, who have been held for 180 days as of 2 May, they 
will have to be released from jail, according to the new law. 
That mass release of suspected criminals has again alarmed the 
government, which does not rule out a declaration of a state of 
internal disturbance to prevent the release of drug traffickers 
and terrorists. 
  [Begin recording] [Government Minister Fabio Villegas] The 
government would evaluate the situation with the Prosecutor 
General's Office and would jointly make relevant decisions with 
that office. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Has the declaration of a state of 
internal disturbance been ruled out? 
  [Villegas] We are not ruling it out nor are we stating that 
it is going to be decreed. [end recording] 
  On another topic, the government minister described the 
assertions of confessed drug trafficker Gabriel Taboada in 
Washington as absurd and he criticized the position of U.S. 
Senator John Kerry. 
  [Begin Villegas recording] It is absurd and incomprehensible 
that a U.S. senator values the opinion of a criminal, a 
confessed criminal, more than this country's record in the 
struggle against drug trafficking. [end recording] 
  For the government, it is clear the struggle against drug 
trafficking will continue without rest, and not just to please 
someone in particular. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

