<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roosen Holds News Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roosen Holds News Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2304153294 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2304153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Cecilia Pachano; from "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Doctor Gustavo Roosen has assumed the task of 
revitalizing the Venezuelan banking system, after being sworn in 
today at Miraflores Palace as presidential commissioner for the 
reform of the financial system. 
  Roosen will exercise the office simultaneously with his 
current position as chairman of the Board of Trustees of Banco 
Latino. In a lengthy news conference held after being sworn in, 
Roosen presented his six-point plan to rescue the national 
banking system: reaching a solidarity accord with private banks, 
strengthening the Superintendency of Banks, reorganizing Fogade 
[Deposit Guarantee and Banking Protection Fund], reducing 
nominal interest rates and the differential between nominal and 
real interest rates, defining new financial instruments to 
replace the zero-coupon bonds, and establishing a plan of 
rehabilitation or major surgery for banks assisted by Fogade. 
  [Begin Roosen recording] If we are able to strike a pact of 
solidarity regarding what I mentioned in my initial explanation, 
the country will see a change and will see a restoration in 
confidence, which was key in the case of Banco Latino. 
  I am convinced by the conversations I held yesterday morning 
and last night, which prompted me to accept this difficult task, 
that the government is ready, the Central Bank is ready, and, as 
a result of my contacts with fellow bankers as chairman of the 
Board of Trustees, I am convinced the banks are also ready for 
this solidarity pact. This is key to eliminating the uncertainty 
that affects the financial system at this time. [end recording] 
  Dr. Gustavo Roosen said that meetings with the private banks 
will begin this weekend in an attempt to sign the solidarity 
accord. A 72-hour deadline was set for its signing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

