<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roosen Requests Banks' Agreements </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roosen Requests Banks' Agreements </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2204184494 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 1510 GMT 
22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2204184494 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vicente Briceno from Miraflores Presidential </F>
Palace in Caracas from the "Union Radio News" newscast] 
  [Text] Dr. Gustavo Roosen, who has been appointed special 
commissioner for reforming the financial system, said a few 
minutes ago that within the next 72 hours he intends to 
establish a solidarity pact between commercial banks and the 
Central Bank of Venezuela to preserve the country's financial 
network. 
  Speaking at Miraflores Palace, Dr. Roosen broadly outlined 
the complex situation for reporters. He said this pact is 
intended to clarify the issuance of financial instruments, which 
can help ease the situation by decreasing the issuance of 
zero-coupon bonds and, in place of these bonds, issuing Treasury 
bills of exchange that would be purchased by domestic banks. 
  [Begin Roosen recording] In accepting this important duty, 
we 
intend to coordinate between the Finance Ministry, the 
superintendency of banks, FOGADE [Deposit Guarantee and Banking 
Protection Fund], and the Central Bank of Venezuela in every way 
possible in an effort to establish a solidarity pact to restore 
confidence in the financial system. 
  We will do this by implementing programs that lead to the 
recovery of subsidized banks, gradually reducing the current gap 
between passive and active interest rates in the national 
market, and seeking ways to use the system's financial surpluses 
in the placement of Treasury bills of exchange or financial 
instruments other than zero-coupon bonds, which has been the 
only available mechanism to remove surplus liquidity from 
circulation. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

